Blocks.childText: National. Prayer for the Republic. 235 736. National. 737. National. 1. GREAT God of nations ! now to thee 1.0 God, beneath thy guiding hand, Our hymn of gratitude we raise; Our exiled fathers crossed the sea ; With humble heart, and bending knee, And when they trod the wintry strand, We offer thee our song of praise. With prayer and psalm they worshiped thee. 2. Thy name we bless, Almighty God ! For all the kindness thou hast shown, 2. Thou heard'st, well-pleased, the song, To this fair land the Pilgrims trod,- the prayer; This land we fondly call our own. Thy blessing came; and still its power Shall onward through all ages bear 3. Here, freedom spreads her banner wide, The memory of that holy hour. And casts her soft and hallowed ray;- Here, thou our fathers' steps didst 3. Laws, freedom, truth, and faith in God guide Came with those exiles o'er the waves; In safety, through their dangerous way. And where their pilgrim feet have trod, 4. We praise thee, that the gospel's light, The God they trusted guards their graves. Through all our land, its radiance 4. And here thy name, O God of love, sheds; Their children's children shall adore, Dispels the shades of error's night, Till these eternal hills remove, And heavenly blessings round us spreads. And spring adorns the earth no more. OLD HUNDREDTH, L. M. 738. Thanksgiving. 739. Prayer for the Republic. 1. ETERNAL source of every joy, 1. GOD of our fathers, let thy face Well may thy praise our lips employ, Toward the Republic ever be! While in thy temple we appear, Encompass it with strength and grace, To hail thee, Sovereign of the year ! And law combine with liberty. 2. Wide as the wheels of nature roll, 2. Unto our President impart Thy hand supports and guides the whole, Sustaining trust, discerning sight, The sun is taught by thee to rise, The homage of the loyal heart, And darkness when to vail the skies. The steadfast courage for the right. 3. The flowery spring at thy command, 3. Within our Congress let the fire Perfumes the air, adorns the land; Of patriotic love abide; The summer rays with vigor shine, Its counsels lead, its acts inspire, To raise the corn, to cheer the vine. And in the nation's halls preside. 4. Thy hand, in autumn, richly pours, 4. Upon our Judges let the seal Through all our coasts redundant stores: Of thy divine anointing be,- And winters, softened by thy care, The wisdom calm, the righteous zeal, No more the face of horror wear. The robes of truth and equity. 5. God of our fathers, let thy face 5. Seasons and months, and weeks, and days, Toward the Republic ever be ! Demand successive songs of praise Encompass it with strength and grace, And be the grateful homage paid, And law combine with liberty. With morning light and evening shade. Doxology. 6. Here in thy house let incense rise, PRAISE God, from whom all blessings flow ! And circling Sabbaths bless our eyes, Praise him, all creatures here below ! Till to those lofty heights we soar, Praise him above, ye heavenly host ! Where days and years revolve no more. Praise Father, Son, and Holy Ghost !
